\IEEEPARstart{B}{elief} propagation~\cite{Kschischang2001} on factor graphs plays an important role in the design of iterative receivers for communication systems~\cite{Colavolpe2005,Guo2009,Wo2012}. However, BP sometimes suffers from high or even intractable computational complexity, and thus some messages are heuristically approximated~\cite{Guo2009,Wo2012}. More rigorous solutions to obtain low complexity receivers~\cite{Badiu2012,Badiu2013,Wu2014,Navarro2011,Zhang2015,Sun2015} are proposed based on unified message passing frameworks, such as a combined BP and expectation propagation (EP)~\cite{Minka2001} framework, and a combined  BP and the mean field (MF)~\cite{Winn2005} framework~\cite{Riegler2013}.

In OFDM systems, the frequency-domain channel estimation in  iterative receiver based on combined BP-MF~\cite{Riegler2013} from previous work~\cite{Badiu2012} suffers a very high computational complexity because a large matrix needs to be inverted in each iteration. A reduced-complexity estimation~\cite{Badiu2013} has been proposed at the cost of system performance.  It assumes groups of contiguous channel weights obey a Markov model which provides a adjustable complexity channel estimation algorithm dependent on the length of each group. In addition, the noise precision was also considered as a random variable and estimated by using MF message update rule and the similar method was also used in~\cite{Navarro2011,Zhang2015}.

Recently, Wu \textit{et al.} have derived a time-domain channel taps estimation algorithm~\cite{Wu2014} exploiting BP and EP message update rules. They takes advantage of an approximate method of BP, generalized approximate message-passing (GAMP)~\cite{Rangan2010}, to reduce the computational complexity. This channel estimation algorithm shows the lower complexity and higher bit error rate (BER) performance compared to~\cite{Badiu2012}. However, due to the characteristics of BP update rule, the precision of channel noise can not be estimated using BP-EP algorithm. The receiver was designed with the exact noise precision, which is always unknown in the actual wireless communication environment.

Inspired by~\cite{Wu2014}, we expand the channel estimation to time domain channel taps by stretching the factor graph. To estimate the noise variance, we create a series of hard constraints factor nodes by stretch the factor graph in this paper. We exploit MF rule in the observation nodes, thus the noise variance could be estimated. Enlightened by~\cite{Schniter2011}, for the intensive connection part we applied the GAMP method achieved lower computational complexity. Using Monte-Carlo simulation, we compared the proposed low complexity BP-MF based receivers to the state-of-the-art BP-MF based receiver~\cite{Badiu2012} in the terms of BER performance and convergent rate. Simulation result shown that, the proposed low complexity receiver achieve the same BER performance but with much lower computational complexity than the receiver presented in~\cite{Badiu2012}.

This paper is organized as follows. In Section \ref{Sec:SysMod}, we describe the OFDM system model with its probabilistic representation and factor graph. Based on the unified message passing framework, BP-MF, we calculate the messages passed on the global factor graph in Section \ref{Sec:BPMF}. Performance analyses are given in Section \ref{Sec:sim}.

